Iraq, a country of more than 17 million, using 100,000 troops and 350 tanks invaded and  quickly conquered Kuwait, an oil-rich state, with 1.9 million residents--60 percent of  them foreigners--and an army of 20,300.
Iraq, after accusing Kuwait of much  wrongdoing, claimed it invaded at the request of Kuwaiti revolutionaries.
The U.N.  Security Council condemned the invasion.
Kuwait's U.S. ambassador asked for  American military intervention.
President Bush froze all Iraqi assets in the U.S., blocked  Iraqi imports and, for their protection, froze Kuwaiti assets under U.S. jurisdiction.
The  Pentagon diverted a naval group toward the Gulf.
Oil prices soared. 
